Loan Data Analysis by Jack Bae

Introduction

Prosper (www.prosper.com) is a peer-to-peer marketplace lending platform. Here is an explanation of Prosper from their website:

Prosper allows people to invest in each other in a way that is financially and socially rewarding. On Prosper, borrowers list loan requests between $2,000 and $35,000 and individual investors invest as little as $25 in each loan listing they select. Prosper handles the servicing of the loan on behalf of the matched borrowers and investors.

And the process of how peer-to-peer lending at Prosper works:

  • Borrowers choose a loan amount, purpose and post a loan listing.
  • Investors review loan listings and invest in listings that meet their criteria.
  • Once the process is complete, borrowers make fixed monthly payments and investors receive a portion of those payments directly to their Prosper account.

The Prosper Loan data analyzed here contains 113,937 records last updated on 03/11/2014.

While exploring the dataset, I found the need to create new variables and data frames. - New variables: ListingCreationYear, ListingCategoryName, CreditScoreAverage - New data frames: loansFrom2009 (loan data after July 12, 2009), loansTo2009 (loan data before July 12, 2009)

Univariate Plots Section

Is there a trend in the number of Prosper loans?

The number of loans by year graph shows that the number of loans increased from 2006 to 2009 but decreased in 2009 due to the global financial crisis. Loans increased again starting in 2010 through 2013. The decrease in loans can be possibily explained by not having full year data for 2014.

## [1] "2005-11-09 20:44:28.847000000" "2014-03-10 12:20:53.760000000"

Checking the range of loan listing creation date, the data confirms that the most recent data for 2014 is March 10, confirming 2014 data does not contain full year data.

What is the distribution of loans by credit grade?

I was interested in investigating who uses peer-to-peer lending platform. One way of looking the data was throuth the credit grade that Prosper created. The credit grade data for data before July 12, 2009 shows a normal distribution of data. Prosper moved to a new rating system starting July 12, 2009.

Post-2009 credit grade has been renamed as Prosper Rating. Although it is showing a normal distribution similar to pre-2009 credit grade distribution, the Prosper Rating is showing fewer applicants with the highest and the lowest distribution.

Distribution of Credit Scores of Prosper Applicants

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##    10.0   670.0   690.0   695.6   730.0   890.0     591

In further understanding Prosper applicants, I have plotted credit score of applicants. The dataset provided fields of lower and upper credit score range. The data here is the average of the lower and upper range.

According to study by ValuePenguin, the average American credit score is 695, which is almost identical the score of 695.6 of Prosper applicants. This shows that Prosper applicants are not skewed towards either low or high credit score applicants. THe normal distribution of the plot further supports this finding.

Distribution of risk score built by Prosper

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##    1.00    4.00    6.00    5.95    8.00   11.00   29084

The Prosper Score is a custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The higher Prosper Score indicates the lowest risk users. The Prosper Score shows a different distribution from Prosper Rating data. This indicates the Prosper Score is calculated based on multiple factors.

Distribution of loan term

## 
##    12    36    60 
##  1614 87778 24545

After learning who used Prosper’s service, I was interested in how the Prosper lending service was used. The distribution of loan term shows that approximately 77% of the loans were 36 month loans. It is followed by 21.5% of 60 month loans and 1.5% of loans being 12 month loans.

Distribution of Loan Status

Next, I was interested in the current status of Prosper loans. Most of the loan status is current. It is followed by completed, charged off, and defaulted loan status.

Distribution of Loans by Listing Category

Observing the plot, the most common category the borrower selected when posting their listing is auto. It is followed by debt consolidation and home improvement.

Number of Current Credit Lines

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##    0.00    7.00   10.00   10.32   13.00   59.00    7604

The number of current credit lines at the time when credit profile was pulled ranges from 0 to 59, with average of 10.32.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##    0.00    6.00    9.00    9.26   12.00   54.00    7604

The number of open credit lines at the time when credit profile was pulled shows a similar distribution with current credit lines. The number of loans by open credit lines ranges from 0 to 54, with average of 9.26.

Number of Loans by Income Range

The income range data for borrowers show that the $25,000-49,999 income bracket request most loans, followed by $50,000-74,999 income range.

Distribution of Total Prosper Loans

Data shows that most of the Prosper applicants were first-time borrowers. This was to be expected because of Prosper’s short history (founded in 2005).

Distribution of Loan by Amount

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    1000    4000    6500    8337   12000   35000

The distribution of loan amount shows a median amount of $6,500. The plot shows significant number of loans were increments of $5,000 with plots showing spikes in loan amount of $5,000, $10,000, $15,000, and $20,000.

Number of Loans by Originial Loan Amount

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     0.0   131.6   217.7   272.5   371.6  2251.5

The distribution of monthly loan payment shows median of $217.7. The plot shows most loan payment under $500 per month. With maximum payment of $2,251, this plot also shows flexibility in loan payment, which could be one factor in using Prosper loan service.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The Prosper loan dataset contains 113,937 loan data across 81 variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

In investigating the Prosper loan dataset, I was interested in who uses peer-to-peer lending service. The univariate plots revealed that many high income people used Prosper loan service. I was surprised and intrigued by this trend. I would like to investigate further categorize which people are more likely to take more loans and for what reason.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

In analysis of the dataset, I found the need to create a listing name for ListingCategory, where it originally had numerical values. Also, I found that the ListingCatoryYear would be helpful in seeing trends in listings year to year and CreditScoreAverage variable to have a single reference point for credit score instead of having a lower and upper range.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I created ListingCreationYear, ListingCategoryName, and CreditScoreAverage variables to the dataset in assisting analyzing Prosper loan dataset.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

It was interesting to see how much the 2009 Global financial crisis had impacted the number of Prosper loans initiated that year. I created ListingCreationYear to show prosper loan by year instead of showing continuous data variable.

Reflection

Investigating the Prosper Loan dataset, I gained insight into the peer-to-peer lending service. I had no idea on who used this service and the APR the users enjoyed. In investigating the dataset, I was most interested in who uses Prosper’s service, how they used the service, and for what purpose. The biggest struggle was first with the ggplot syntax and organizing plots so that it was easy for the user to interpret the data. The second major challenge for me was finding interesting trends from the dataset. Finding trends and relationships from 81 variables was a challenge with the number of variables and data. I found that by dividing the variables into similar and smaller pieces, I was able to decipher data more easily.

One interesting future work could be finding trends that could influence Prosper Rating. It is likely that the current Prosper Rating does not account for applicants based on economy situation. During a recession like 2009, there could be factors more relevant to risk factors than during an economic boom. Having a dynamic Prosper Rating based on economic sitaution could help filter applicants effectively and ultimately bring more profits to Prosper.
